Participant Information

Here, we examine participant demographics, such as their age and gender, in addition to information about their work industry and experience. Overall, our sample is highly skewed in terms of gender. A representative average participant would be a man who works in a relatively large technology company with some years of experience.

## Testing

No Covariates - Baseline Model

## anova testing
condition_anova <- aov(data = analysis, rating ~ Condition)
summary(condition_anova)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## Condition     3   55.7  18.583   6.324 0.000317 ***
## Residuals   596 1751.3   2.938                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## follow-up t-tests, bonferroni correction
pairwise.t.test(analysis$rating, analysis$Condition, p.adjust.method = "bonferroni")
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using t tests with pooled SD 
## 
## data:  analysis$rating and analysis$Condition 
## 
##                      Man_Traditional Man_Nontraditional Woman_Nontraditional
## Man_Nontraditional   0.3344          -                  -                   
## Woman_Nontraditional 0.3611          1.0000             -                   
## Woman_Traditional    0.4084          0.0013             0.0015              
## 
## P value adjustment method: bonferroni
## linear model
condition_model <- lm(data = analysis, rating ~ Condition)

# test for heteroscedasticity to determine if use of robust standard errors is justified
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(condition_model)

bptest(condition_model)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  condition_model
## BP = 9.3403, df = 3, p-value = 0.02509
condition_model$vcovHC_ <- vcovHC(condition_model)
coefs_conditions <- coeftest(condition_model, vcov. = condition_model$vcovHC_)
coefs_conditions
## 
## t test of coefficients:
## 
##                               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)                    7.63816    0.11867 64.3645  < 2e-16 ***
## ConditionMan_Nontraditional   -0.37816    0.20084 -1.8829  0.06020 .  
## ConditionWoman_Nontraditional -0.37149    0.18696 -1.9871  0.04737 *  
## ConditionWoman_Traditional     0.36184    0.17847  2.0274  0.04306 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
ci_conditions <- coefci(condition_model, vcov. = condition_model$vcovHC_)
ci_conditions
##                                     2.5 %       97.5 %
## (Intercept)                    7.40509494  7.871220847
## ConditionMan_Nontraditional   -0.77259672  0.016280932
## ConditionWoman_Nontraditional -0.73866411 -0.004318344
## ConditionWoman_Traditional     0.01132734  0.712356867

Based on the previous tests, we can detect that there are significant differences between conditions. This result is shown in the ANOVA test, for which post hoc testing indicates differences between the Woman_Traditional condition and the conditions Man_Nontraditional and Woman_Nontraditional. We follow this testing with linear models to more clearly capture the quantitative differences between ratings.

Specifically, the baseline candidate received a rating, on average of 7.64 (7.41, 7.87). In comparison, men with a nontraditional education were rated lower, by an average of -0.38 (-0.77, 0.02). Women with a nontraditional education were also reated lower than men with a traditional education, by an average of -0.37 (-0.74, 0). Finally, women with a traditional education were actually rated higher than men with a traditional education, by an average of 0.36 (0.01, 0.71).

Applicant Attributes

The previous analysis focused specifically on the conditions shown. we are also interested in the qualities of these conditions, such as the applicant_gender & applicant_education variables. This will give us a clearer statistical understanding of the input of each quality of the applicant. At this point forward, we use linear models, rather than ANOVA and t-testing. This is to make the content more consistent with the techniques learned in the course.

applicant_model <- lm(data = analysis, rating ~ applicant_gender * applicant_education)

# test for heteroscedasticity to determine if use of robust standard errors is justified
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(applicant_model)

bptest(applicant_model)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  applicant_model
## BP = 9.3403, df = 3, p-value = 0.02509
applicant_model$vcovHC_ <- vcovHC(applicant_model)
coefs_applicants <- coeftest(applicant_model, vcov. = applicant_model$vcovHC_)
coefs_applicants
## 
## t test of coefficients:
## 
##                                                  Estimate Std. Error t value
## (Intercept)                                       7.63816    0.11867 64.3645
## applicant_genderwoman                             0.36184    0.17847  2.0274
## applicant_educationnontrad                       -0.37816    0.20084 -1.8829
## applicant_genderwoman:applicant_educationnontrad -0.35518    0.28103 -1.2638
##                                                  Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)                                       < 2e-16 ***
## applicant_genderwoman                             0.04306 *  
## applicant_educationnontrad                        0.06020 .  
## applicant_genderwoman:applicant_educationnontrad  0.20678    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
ci_applicants <- coefci(applicant_model, vcov. = applicant_model$vcovHC_)
ci_applicants
##                                                        2.5 %     97.5 %
## (Intercept)                                       7.40509494 7.87122085
## applicant_genderwoman                             0.01132734 0.71235687
## applicant_educationnontrad                       -0.77259672 0.01628093
## applicant_genderwoman:applicant_educationnontrad -0.90710101 0.19675013

In this case, we observe a significant effect of gender overall, but in the opposite direction which we expected. Women, on average, receive a higher rating than men (0.3618421 higher, p = 0.043064). We also see a slight effect of education (p = 0.0602024). Specifically, the applicants with a nontraditional education background are rated -0.3781579 lower than those with traditional educations. There is no interaction effect observed (p = 0.2067803).

We add risk aversion scores to the model to capture individual differences in regards to the amount of risk one may be confortable taking on. It does not change the estimations from the previous model.
